<h2>Quick Actions: Reverse and Shuffle</h2>

<p>Beyond manual dragging, the tool has two one-click shortcuts:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Reverse order</strong> — flips all pages from last to first. Useful for back-to-front scans.</li>
  <li><strong>Shuffle randomly</strong> — randomises the page order. Useful for quiz or flashcard PDFs where you want a fresh sequence.</li>
  <li><strong>Reset to original</strong> — reverts back to the original page sequence if you want to start over.</li>
</ul>

<h2>What Happens to the PDF Quality?</h2>

<p>
  Nothing changes except the order. The tool uses <a href="https://pdf-lib.js.org/" rel="noopener noreferrer">pdf-lib</a>
  to copy pages from the source document into a new PDF in your specified sequence.
  Fonts, vector graphics, embedded images, and hyperlinks are all transferred without modification.
  There is no rendering step, so there is zero quality loss.
</p>

<h2>Rearranging Pages with pdf-lib (JavaScript)</h2>

<p>If you need to automate page reordering in a Node.js project:</p>

<pre><code>import &#123; PDFDocument &#125; from 'pdf-lib';
import fs from 'fs';

const srcBytes = fs.readFileSync('input.pdf');
const srcPdf = await PDFDocument.load(srcBytes);

const newOrder = [2, 0, 1]; // 0-based page indices
const outPdf = await PDFDocument.create();
const pages = await outPdf.copyPages(srcPdf, newOrder);
pages.forEach(p =&gt; outPdf.addPage(p));

const outBytes = await outPdf.save();
fs.writeFileSync('reordered.pdf', outBytes);</code></pre>

<h2>Rearranging PDF Pages on Different Devices</h2>

<h3>Mac — Preview</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Open the PDF in Preview.</li>
  <li>Show the thumbnail sidebar: <strong>View → Thumbnails</strong>.</li>
  <li>Drag thumbnails into the order you want.</li>
  <li>Save with <strong>File → Export as PDF</strong>.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Windows — Microsoft Edge</h3>
<p>
  Edge's built-in PDF viewer does not support reordering. Use the browser-based tool above — it works in any browser including Edge with no extension required.
</p>

<h3>iPhone / Android</h3>
<p>
  Open the PDF Page Reorder tool in your mobile browser. The drag interface works with touch — press and hold the ⠿ handle, then drag the row to its new position.
</p>

